<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n26268p"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26268p">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26268p"> 268(p)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> <span class="strike"><span class="striketext">7</span></span> ploughox <span class="strike"><span class="striketext">7</span></span></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[Public Offences and their Punishment]</font>&mdash;Take some of those offences whose sanction was <i>sacratio capitis</i>. Breach of duty resulting from the fiduciary relation between patron and client, maltreatment of a parent by his child, exposure or killing of a child by its father contrary to the Romulian rules, the ploughing up or removal of a boundary stone, the slaughter of a <mark>plough-ox</mark> &mdash; all these were capital offences; the offender, by the formula, <i>sacer esto</i>, was devoted to the infernal gods. <small> &ldquo;ROMAN LAW&rdquo; <a name="EBRL2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EBRL2"><cite title="source">Encyclopaedia Britannica</cite></a>, 11th edit. (1911) 534</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
